segments.text: Crowne Plaza Hotel in Dallas.
Farmer's Branch.
Farmer's Branch.
Sorry about that.
Don't let the city manager hear you say it.
OK. And this is Bob Cornish, and I'm interviewing Bill Shevlin today of Farmer's Branch.
And Bill has a rather varied background in planning and has brought a lot of resources to the Texas scene.
Bill, would you like to start with your planning education and whatever your first experience was in Texas planning?
Well, my original education was a bachelor's of architecture from Texas A&M, and I was in the service, and then I came back to Fort Worth and worked in architecture, and

decided that I, that that was too limiting, and I went off to, made application, was accepted, went off to the University of Pennsylvania in 1961, in the fall of 61, and entered the joint program there, and was there two years and ended up with a master's degree in architecture and a master's degree in city planning.
And following that, immediately following that, I came to
Back to Texas, really not knowing what I was going to do for sure, but I came to Dallas to meet the man who had given me a fellowship at Pennsylvania for two years.
We lived in Dallas, and he insisted that when I had lunch with him after lunch, he insisted that he take me over to meet a very close friend of his that he referred to as Sprung.
who turned out to be Marvin Springer.
And so he took me to Sprung's office.
And I think the conversation went something like this.
Sprung, you need somebody on your staff from the University of Pennsylvania.
Shevlin, you need to be in Dallas working with Springer.
And before the afternoon was out, I was working for Springer.
He had not intended to hire anybody, and I had not intended to go to work for anybody in Dallas.
And I was subsequently with Marvin for about two years as an associate in his firm.
At one time, we had Marvin and myself as an associate, Doyle Smith as an associate who had a background in civil engineering, and Frank Osgood, who had a background in economics.
And he had come from Tulsa.
He had come from, he may have come from Tulsa.
I know his brother was involved in planting up there, but he may have come from Tulsa.
It was during that period of time when I was with Marvin, a lot of our work was centered around 701 projects, which I found, as Marvin found,
was very, very difficult to do in Texas.
There was a lot of hand-holding and not a lot of prospect for implementation after the fact.
The biggest project I worked on with Marvin, public project while I was with him, was the city of Galveston.
We did the comprehensive plan for the city of Galveston during that period.
And I did a lot of work on the housing
analysis and component community facilities and all of that.
And we did work in other cities, 701 planning.
He was doing some work in Denison at that time, in Plano.
And I can't remember all the cities now.
There were a number of them.
And I was not involved in all of them.
I was involved in most of them in one way or another.
Galveston was the one that I was involved in
beginning to end.
You may say anything about Marvin, my view of Marvin.
Marvin was, at that time, and I've had occasion to work with him in a different capacity on a couple of occasions since.
One was with respect to the Flower Mound Newtown planning, which he represented the city of Flower Mound, and later I worked with him when he was
representing the city of Plano, and I was working with a major tract of land out there.
But Marvin, I considered the time spent with Marvin to be very valuable postgraduate work, because I found him to be very knowledgeable.
I found him to be the best I've ever met in my entire life in getting people to work together towards some objectives which they may not share in common.
He was a great facilitator.
I say was only because he retired from active practice.
By the time he was in active practice, he was very people-oriented, very much capable of seeing problems freshly and dealing with them.
One of the things he used to say quite often was, I'm not a solution walking around looking for a problem.
His population estimates held up better.
If you go back and check them, you'll find they've held up better than probably any, certainly any at that time, and maybe any since because of the way he went about doing it.
And I just think he probably more than anyone else made a major contribution to what we consider to be planning in the state of Texas.
He was a great innovator in the area of ordinances.
Just because many, many cities in Texas have ordinances which he prepared 20, 25 years ago that became obsolete, it's not his fault because they were very much on the mark at the time.
It's just that the city's never got around to revising.
Farmer's Branch is a good example, which is now going through a comprehensive planning process for the first time.
will sometime within the next year revise Marvin's zoning ordinance for the first time.
At any rate, Marvin made a great contribution, and I consider it to be a real privilege to have a chance to work with him.
Everything I learned from Marvin I've used to advantage since.
How long were you with Marvin?
I was with Marvin for about two years and left.
only because I received a phone call one day as I was at work sitting on the drafting stool working on a plan.
And the person on the other end of the line said, this is Don Foley.
I'm head of the Department of City Regional Planning at Berkeley.
And we have a position to fill on the staff next year.
We have a professor going on sabbatical.
It was Mel Scott.
You've been recommended to us.
Would you be interested in coming to Berkeley for a year?
And so I thought about three seconds, and I said yes.
And so that's the reason I left here.
You were there for a year?
I was there for a year, and I was offered another year to stay there for another year.
I was also offered a position to go over to Berkeley and become the city planner.
I was offered a position in Oakland,
offered a position by Alan Jacobs when he went to San Francisco to come head up urban design in San Francisco.
And I didn't.
Norman Lynn was an Oakland.
Norman Lynn was an Oakland.
And I did none of those things because in the middle of my time in California, I got married to a Dallas girl who got homesick and wanted to come back.
Interesting change in career direction.
That's right.
So that's the reason I probably ended up back in Dallas.

And Marvin was, one of the other things that happened when I worked with Marvin is that I immediately became very aware of the professional organizations and also the educational organizations in Texas relating to planning because Marvin was what I consider to be a professional's professional.
He was very much behind planning education.
He was
It was one of the people who had been instrumental in establishing AIP as a professional organization and a force in Texas, along with people like Ralph Elliford and Bill... Who am I trying to say?
No, and... John Cunningham.
I mean, John Cunningham, not Bill.
John Cunningham.
I know what Bill Cunningham... John Cunningham.
Bill Singleton out of Louisiana, people like that.
And I immediately, through Marvin, came into contact with all these people who were also very, very fine people.
I'm trying to establish when the chapter was created.
It was originally the Gulf Southwest chapter.
It was in existence before I came in 1961.
So I would say that it was created probably during the time that Marvin was still planning director in Dallas, a period which was from 1950 to 1959 sometime.
So I would say it was probably four or five years before that day was established.
Oh, it was Marvin.
By the way, Marvin is writing the history of planning in Dallas.
Is he?

I would say that the time I came to Texas in 1961 and at the time I left Texas in 1963 to go to California and at the time I came back in 1965, left in 65, came back in 66, that nothing had changed, that AIP as a professional organization was relatively weak.
because there weren't enough planners with any credentials to create any kind of critical mass and therefore any influence.
By far Marvin was the most influential person in the state with respect to the state.
He had a tremendous standing with state agencies in particular with the Texas State Highway Department.
So he was the one who
When it was necessary to get somebody out front, Marvin was usually the one that was out front.
The other thing that was, I think, fair to say is that planning education in Texas was practically nonexistent, as we would think of it today.
And both of those things were very...
The only program at all was at UT Austin.
That's right.
And it wasn't... Hugo was down there, but it wasn't really much of a program.
It was more of a...
I don't know what to say, specialty within architecture, which is the worst place, weren't the worst place, the only worst place in architecture, or equally worst place to be engineering.
At any rate, it just didn't exist.
And so consequently, my involvement at that time, when I was with Marvin, was rather limited.
There was really no place here for me to...
to teach anything, and I also thought at that time I hadn't learned enough to teach anything, so that worked out fine.
That doesn't bother some of our current students.
I understand.
But the other side of it, with respect to AIP, I did start getting involved with AIP, and Marvin encouraged people who worked for him to do that, but it was... And I can't remember.
I know that the first...
The first section meeting I went to was, I think there were two people there, and they were both wondering why they were there, and I think Bob Mitchell was one of them, as I recall.
Maybe John Greer was the other one, but it was pretty discouraging.
At any rate, when I left and went to Berkeley, that was a very stimulating experience.
I was there during the middle of the free speech movement, and I went down to the
to the commons and watch Mario Savio.

And I like to pride myself in having the intelligence to be standing in front of the administration building the day that Carol Doda came out and did her famous act on the balcony of the administration building.
But the students were stimulating.
The environment was stimulating.
Although I did, just as a quick aside, as I said earlier,

find myself at Berkeley in the same situation I found myself in the U.S. and Pennsylvania a few years earlier, right in the middle of a fight for turf between the social policy planners and the fiscal planners.
So there was nothing dull about it.
Again, as we had at Penn when I was there, we had a real galaxy of people, and they made a big impression on me.
However, when I came back, I must have come back infused with a lot of
energy and enthusiasm and so forth.
And let me say also parenthetically that I have never held a position in a public agency.
I've never worked directly for a public agency as an employee.
When I came back, we did a lot of work for agencies when I was with Marvin.
And I had a lot of dealings with public agencies.
And I was around enough so that sometimes, particularly in a place like Galveston, I wondered if I was on their payroll or on Marvin's payroll.
And he wondered that sometimes, too.
But, so my perspective is more from that of an outsider who's done a lot of work with public agencies but never within public agencies.
And when I came back, I took a position with a firm, local firm in Dallas.
At that time it was called Harrell and Hamilton.
It's now called Omnicwine.
Was that Harrell Hamilton?
No, no, no.
Harrell, George Harrell and E.T.
Hamilton.
It's now changed.
While it was there, it changed its name to Omniclan.
And I was in charge of planning and urban design for them.
And we did a variety of things, although none of them, with the exception of the Dallas Convention Center, do I consider to have been especially noteworthy.
But things that I was involved in during that period of time.
However, when I did come back, I really found myself thrown into the middle of AIP.
AIA nationally, AIP nationally, AIP locally.
Also, when I came back, I was asked upon my return by TCU to start a course on urban design in their urban studies program, which I did.
I did, and I used to commute.
For about a year, I commuted several nights a week after work to TCU to teach that course, and I finally gave it up after a year because I knew it was just too hard.
I just couldn't do it.
and didn't want to do it, I should put it that way, because there were a lot of demands on time otherwise.
Is that an animal?
What?
TCU in Fort Worth.
In Fort Worth.
But it was a long drive after a day's work.
But I did set that program up for them, and I understand it did continue for a few years after that, other people teaching it.
When I got back, I did get very much involved at a,
local level, at state level, and national level in AIP.
And I got involved at a local level, not so much at the state level, but at a national level in AIA.
I became section director of the, it was called the Dallas-Fort Worth section originally, as I recall.
And one of the things, I did a couple of things.
One of them was I got the name change to North Central Texas section.
The other thing I did was to, I realized soon after I got into the organization, it was one of the reasons why I wanted to become section director, there were no bylaws.
And one reason why there were no bylaws is that the chapter had no bylaws.
So I wrote the original bylaws myself.
I wrote them for the North Central Texas section.

Those bylaws, because they were the only ones that existed among all the sections of the chapter, for that matter, ended up being the ones that were used as a model to construct the first chapter bylaws.
So then we started working on trying to execute.
By that time, more climbers were coming into Texas.
The 701 programs were dissipating, winding down.
Towns were growing to a size where they could afford to hire planners.
The population growth in Texas had gotten to that point.
The whole thing was getting better in terms of an environment.
However, there was a lot of friction between the planners and the engineers, for example.
And not at that time to a great extent with the architects, but with the engineers with respect to who was going to do planning.
And he was qualified to do planning.
And that was a major issue at the time.
I think Mary Lou Henry was involved in that situation with the engineers.
Yes, she was.
And I was involved in it to some extent.
One of the things I was involved with also at that period of time was helping to get the state AIP in a stronger position with respect to state legislation affecting planners, planning and planners.

with respect to the way in which the state viewed the role of cities, municipalities, in having some responsibility toward planning, which at that time they didn't, you know, the old thing, the old problem of zoning as a substitute for planning was rampant in Texas as it is still largely today.
During, in the, around the mid-60s,
or just after I got back, around 67, 68, 69, in that period, I was involved with, well, I was involved with AIP.
I was chairman for three years of the national, AIP National Urban Design Committee.
We had lots of real luminaries on that committee, and I was fortunate to be able to get them to come to meetings.
We had about six meetings a year, and I could get about a 95% participation.
They paid their own way.

from real, really first-class, well-known people, because by that time, urban design was becoming a topic which was widely discussed and written about, and people were interested in pushing it along who were involved in it.
Of course, you had local here.
You had Wyoming Lou.
Well, that was later.
That was later.
That came later, and I'll tell that story about how we got Waymang, too, if you'd like to know that.
because it's all tied in together.
I was also the one that got finally, I said, this is nuts.
When the AIP started establishing technical departments, I said, let's convert this to a technical department.
And I went to the board and said, we want to convert this to a technical department.
And they said they had two, I think, at that time.
One might have been regional planning, but I can't remember at this point.
They said, well,
We just barely got the other two established with enough petition signatures.
And you'll never get urban design to be established as technical department.
There's not enough interest.
But at any rate, we went ahead and promoted it and petitioned it.
And when we submitted it to the board, and I remember that day I took it in there, and Paul Davidoff almost fell out of his chair and was on the board at that time.
Because I said, well, we've done it, and we have twice as many signatures
we need to petition this into a technical department, and considerably more than the other two.
So that got accomplished.
I was also involved.
I can't remember exactly when it happened, but I was involved in promoting the idea of the urban joint program between AIP and AIA, Urban Design Assistance Team.
And I think I went on the third one,
Second or third one they did, which was in Linden, Massachusetts.
And I worked a great deal in trying to get that program and knit it together and keeping it going between the two parties.
It's mostly architecture now, isn't it?
I don't know.
I've been so out of touch with it for so long.
Let me say, it was originally conceived by the AIA.
And I, along with a few other people, were the ones who pushed
the AIP into it and sort of insisted that it be a joint program.
So I'm sure that's continued.
Well, I'm sure it hadn't continued, particularly since we changed to the APA concept.
I don't think there's been enough, which I was not in favor of.
There's not enough glue there to make it stick.
At any rate, you asked about Wei Ming Wu.
Interesting, I'll tell you the story about that, the history of that, if you want to know how he got here.
From Minneapolis, where he was from.
Yeah, he came from Minneapolis, where he was from.
One of the things that happened when I came back from Berkeley is I looked around and I said, hey, there's no urban design.
The city of Dallas has no urban design, anything.
And they barely had a comprehensive planning program.
So Alden Deal was the planning director at that time.
How do you spell his last name?
D-E-Y-O.
He worked under Marvin, and he was the planning director.
And Alden had a very, in my opinion, and I used to tell him this, fairly narrow idea of what comprehensive planning was.
And Alden and I spent a lot of time talking about urban design and why urban design should be in the program.
After about a year and a half, it happened that there was a reorganization of the planning department, which Alden initiated.
And we managed to get urban design.
I managed to convince him that urban design should be a confluent.
Originally, it was going to be a committee or sort of like a minor function within the long range planning aspect of the plan.

And I argued with him and then later, a little bit later, with Jim Schroeder, who was very sympathetic, and with George Schroeder, who was the city manager at that time, that it should be a full-fledged division.
Was it Schroeder who was a landscape architect?
He may have been.
I don't know Jim's background.
From A&M.
He could have been.
I don't know Jim's background.
At any rate, we got it established on paper.
And then I said, oh, my God, it's on paper, but they don't have a staff.
How are they going to get a staff?
Because there weren't very many people around, and they wouldn't want to pay very much money at that initial and so forth.
So one day I went down to...
George, I mean, to Jim Schroeder's office, and I said, Jim, I got an idea.
He said, what is it?
I said, look, you've got an urban design division established on paper, but you don't have it staffed, and you don't have really enough funds to staff it right now.
If we don't do something with it, it's going to die.
It's going to just wither, and it won't be there anymore, or it'll be lost in the shop, or it'll be relegated back to what it shouldn't have been in the first place.
He said, what do you propose?
And I said, well,

What I think we should do is set up a temporary committee or preferably a task force, because I see it having a short life, to help advise the planning department during this period on urban design and to help it find the person to head up the department for this division, I should say.
He says, find with me if you can get George Schrader to agree with it.
So I said, let me have your phone, and I called George Schrader upstairs.
He was assistant city manager at that time.
I said, I'd like to come up and talk to you.
He said, fine.
So I went up and I made a proposal to him.
He said, I think that's a great idea.
How do you think we should do it?
And I said, well, it seems to me that you really need to ask one of the professional organizations to set it up rather than trying to do it yourself.
Because I said two things.
That's one.
Second thing is it should report to the city manager, not to the planning department.
It should be an advisory group.
Because among other things, it needs to have independence.
And number two, you need to be able to kick it out when the time comes.
So he said, OK, who do you suggest?
I said, well, I'd like to suggest AIP, but they're not strong enough to do it at this point.
I said, so I think what should happen is you should ask AIA to do it, just strong enough to do it, but with some conditions that AIP and ASLA need to be involved in it directly.
put together the committee.

So that letter was issued, written by George Schroeder and signed by Scott McDonald, the city manager at that time, inviting the AIA to set up this new function, which I suggested to George be called the Urban Design Task Force.
And it did come into existence.
I am dismayed to say it's still in existence.
It should have gone out of existence a long time ago.
It's now become...
a professional country club, one of those things you need to have your name on.

At any rate, we then set about finding somebody to head up this thing, and we were asked to talk to different people, and it happened that along about this time there was a national AIP conference, a convention in Minneapolis, and Jim Schroeder asked me

along with a couple of other people, while we were out there to talk with Wei Ming Wu, who was being considered, and see if we felt he would be a good person to employ as the head of the urban design division, and if so, to help the city convince him that he should come here.
And we did, in fact, meet with Wei Ming, and we did, in fact...
do a lot of talking with him.
And I think Wayming has said on a number of occasions that one of the main reasons he made the decision to come was because the city did have the Urban Design Task Force.
And he was impressed with the amount of support it had.
And he felt that he could get the support out of the community and the professional organizations to allow him to do the job.
So that's the story of how Wayming Lou got to Dallas.
And he was here for quite a few years.
About six or eight years, and he was...

The blunt truth of the matter is that he was pushed out by George Schrader, the city manager, because, well, there are several sides to the story, and I won't go into all that, but I will say that George and the city council, as a matter of fact, at that time, simply were not in sympathy with what Wayman was trying to accomplish.

I think there was also a test of wills there and some other things, but the long and the short of it is that the city manager had the power to make conditions in Dallas untenable for Wei Ming to remain.
So he left.
And now went to the lower town, head up the lower town redevelopment program in St. Paul and was doing a bang-up job there, something I knew he would do.
Wei Ming had quite an influence, I think, not only on the
on Dallas planning.
He certainly had an influence on with regard to raising expectations of what could actually be accomplished in public environments.
But he also, I think, raised those level of expectations in the state because he was truly a national figure.
And I think people in the profession recognize that.
Well, it seemed to me that I read in one of the
that at the time, the city of Dallas had the largest number of dollars budgeted for urban design of any city in the United States.
I'm sure that, well, I'm not sure.
I'll take that as based value being true.
It's certainly possible, because it was a very large budget, and Wei Ming had brought a cadre of very skilled people in there, and they were doing very good things.
And it certainly was a model for the rest of the state, at least.
Yeah.
And I think in some respects, I think it still is.
I do not know, because I have not been involved with planning education at all in Texas since my commute to TCU back in 67, I guess it was, or whatever that year I was there.
Did you know Tom ?
Yes, I knew.
Tom was a student of mine at NM.
And he has recently set up his own shop.
I had heard that.
But he was with the department for years, and I think always remained very interested in urban design.
I'm sure he was very supportive of leaving the room.
Oh, I know he was.
Yeah, I know that's a fact.
In 1969, I really left professional life, and have not gone back.
and went into business.
